    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-01-11T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-01-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="483"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d483">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">841.857 L 97/126½</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to President
                            <persName type="to">Wilson</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-01-11">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 11, 1916</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. President</hi>: I have your comment upon the
                    proposed reply of the German Government in the Lusitania case. With your views I
                    entirely agree.</p>
                <p>Yesterday I had an interview with Count von Bernstorff, of which I enclose a
                    memorandum which was made immediately after I talked with him.<note n="97"
                        xml:id="d483fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_516">p. 516</ref>.</note> You
                    will perceive that I took very much the line of approach which you suggest in
                    your letter.</p>
                <p>Faithfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
